@subsection site_death_sec Site death

@section framework_usage_sec Usage

An app that uses this library is expected to create a number of threads for various activities.
An action will typically be completed by a chain of ITC (Inter-Thread Commiunication) messages starting from
the first thread that receives an event. This will typically correspond to an event received by topic subscription.
One or more of the threads may publish something down this ITC chain. This will be done by sending an ITC message
to the single publisher thread, as mentioned before. Ultimately, it will come down to socket calls.
Berkeley sockets will be used, not boost asio or std asio. The sockets will be set up as non-blocking
so the EWOULDBLOCK error needs to be dealt with. This must not be by busy looping directly until the operation
succeeds. Instead the task needs to be handled off asynchronously. Publishers and Subscribers can run at different speeds
which is why we have to handle backpressure. When a subscriber is slow the publisher may encounter
the socket buffer being full. When that happens the publisher gets EWOULDBLOCK. Just retrying for ever might not be enough.
But there must be some retrying. Eventually the connection to the slow consumer should be terminated.

The application as a whole needs to run an event loop (via Reactor::run) which will not stop until the
application receives a termination event, typically a SIGTERM.
Threads will need to be registered with the Reactor and they will start as soon as the event loop is started.

@section Coding rules and other project conventions:

File Naming and Structure: Use PascalCase for filenames and types
(e.g., Logger.hpp). Follow the "one type per header" rule, with the
exception of the pimpl idiom (pimpl code all goes in the cpp file of the class that uses the pimpl).
Abstract types should have the Interface suffix.

Code Style and Naming: Use 1TBS for brace style. Variable names should
use snake_case, while type names should use PascalCase. Do not use UPPERCASE_TOKENS.
Brace initialisation should be used for data members.
Data members should have a trailing underscore.
That should not have a leading underscore, nor contain any double underscores.
They should not start with 'm_' or 'd_' or anything like that.
The trailing underscore indicates they are private.

General Practices: Prefer explicit nullptr comparisons (e.g., if (ptr == nullptr)).
Avoid one-letter variable names except for loop counters.
Use \#pragma once instead of C-style include guards.

Documentation: All documentation must be in Doxygen format and placed in header files only.
Use \@param to indicate parameter direction ([in], [out], or [in,out]) and use \@returns for non-void functions.
Avoid the doxygen at class directive since it is redundant and its use merely restates the code.
Don't comment the use of RAII or pimpl, since the developer is expected to know these concepts.

Compilation and Safety: Treat all compiler warnings as errors. Use the
[[nodiscard]] attribute for functions that return an error.
Place the destructor first in a class definition.
Single argument constructors must be declared as explicit.

Source File Content: Source files should contain only ASCII characters.

Include Ordering: \#include statements should be grouped and alphabetized within each group in this specific order:
C, C++ (c prefix), System C++, Third Party, and Project. C++ headers (e.g., cerrno) are preferred
over their C counterparts (e.g., errno.h).

The error handling style is to return a value and an error string as a std::tuple. The error string should contain
all the context needed for the error string to be useful (e.g. address already in use should contain the port number).
The type int shall be used to denote the length of a message, not std::size or any other unsigned integer type.
This is because an int is more than large enough to record the size of the largest message that we will support.
The library should not use exceptions as an error handling strategy.

 */
